1. Introduction ¶

This notebook serves as an introduction to the world of visualization of climate data using python.

The data set discussed in this notebook contains historical daily surface temperature data from the model MPI-ESM1-2-LR with the configuration r1i1p1f1 gn. The time period covers the years 1970 to 2009. source: https://esgf-data.dkrz.de/search/cmip6-dkrz/ (File named: tas_day_MPI-ESM1-2-LR_historical_r1i1p1f1_gn_19700101-20091231.nc)

At the moment these are the common methods, for questions and comments please contact me via this form or mail.

2.3 Manipulate / prepare and load datasets ¶

If you want to use only certain temporal or spatial sections, you can prepare your data with the command line tool cdo.

Get the description of the dataset:

cdo sinfo someFile.nc

Get the description of the variables in a dataset:

cdo pardes someFile.nc

selection of certain years:

cdo selyear,1980,1981,1982 inputfil.nc outputfile.nc

select the region europe:

cdo sellonlatbox,-45,60,25,65 someGlobalData.nc EUR_outputfile.nc

Selection of the annual mean of the season DJF (winter) of temperature data (tas) of the region europe between the years 1990-2000:

cdo yearmean -select,season=DJF -sellonlatbox,-45,60,25,65 -selvar,tas someGlobalData.nc EUR_DJF_yearmean_tas_1990-2000_outputfile.nc

cmap="Spectral_r"

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 8), dpi=96)
ax = plt.subplot(projection=ccrs.PlateCarree())

# data["tas"].mean("time") -> mean over all timesteps
ds = data["tas"].mean("time")
lon = ds.coords["lon"]; lon_idx = ds.dims.index("lon")
wrap_data, wrap_lon = add_cyclic_point(ds, coord=lon, axis=lon_idx)
mappable = ax.contourf(
    wrap_lon, data.lat,
    wrap_data, transform=ccrs.PlateCarree(),
    cmap=cmap, levels=14, # levels defines how much colors should used (try 8 or 80)
    add_colorbar=False,
)
    
''' this is simple, but without adding a cyclic point it will display an uncolored line in the middle bc of index borders
mappable = data["tas"].mean("time").plot.contourf(
    ax=ax, cmap="Spectral_r",
    levels=33, add_colorbar=False
)
'''

ax.set_title("Mean temperatures in GCM data")

# ---- colorbar ----
divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
cax = divider.append_axes("right", '3%', pad='3%', axes_class=mpl.pyplot.Axes)
cbar = ax.get_figure().colorbar(mappable, cax=cax, orientation="vertical")
cbar.set_label("temperature in K")

ax.set_ylabel("Latitude")
ax.set_xlabel("Longitude")

ax.set_yticklabels([x for x in ax.get_yticks()])
ax.set_xticklabels([x for x in ax.get_xticks()])
ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(cticker.LatitudeFormatter())
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(cticker.LongitudeFormatter())

ax.add_feature(cartopy.feature.BORDERS)
ax.gridlines(alpha=0.6, linewidth=0.5)
ax.coastlines(); # if this does not work, try: ax.add_feature(cartopy.feature.GSHHSFeature(edgecolor='k'))

3.2 Seasonal comparison ¶

You can select the seasonal data via python and also with cdo on the command line. (cdo it is much faster and easier to reproduce)

#!/bin/bash

inputf=$1
seasons=(djf mam jja son)

set -e

trap 'last_command=$current_command; current_command=$BASH_COMMAND' DEBUG
trap 'echo "\"${last_command}\" command filed with exit code $?."' EXIT

inputf=$1

if [ ! -e $inputf ]
then
        echo "$inputf not found"
        exit
fi

for season in "${seasons[@]}"
do
    echo $season
    cdo yearmean -select,season=$season $inputf ${season}_${inputf}
done
`

Make it executable:

chmod u+x createSeasData.sh
`

Run with:

./createSeasData.sh inputfile.nc
`

After that, there are 4 new files, each of which has the yearmean for its season in every year. (40 years each with one value in this example)

# create figure
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(20,12), subplot_kw={ "projection": ccrs.PlateCarree() }) 
title=f"Seasonal mean temperatures in some example data \n({start_year} - {end_year})"
fig.suptitle(title)

row, col = 0, 0
for i, season in enumerate(seasons): # plot for every season
    ds = seasons[season][var].mean("time")
    lon = ds.coords["lon"]; lon_idx = ds.dims.index("lon")
    wrap_data, wrap_lon = add_cyclic_point(ds, coord=lon, axis=lon_idx)
    mappable = axs[row,col].contourf(
        wrap_lon, ds.lat,
        wrap_data, transform=ccrs.PlateCarree(),
        cmap=cmap, levels=14, vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax,
        add_colorbar=False,
    )
    axs[row,col].set_title(season)
    col += 1; row = row + 1 if col > 1 else row
    col = 0 if col > 1 == 1 else col       
        
plt.tight_layout()

        axs[row,col].set_yticklabels([x for x in axs[row,col].get_yticks()])
        axs[row,col].set_xticklabels([x for x in axs[row,col].get_xticks()])
        axs[row,col].yaxis.set_major_formatter(cticker.LatitudeFormatter())
        axs[row,col].xaxis.set_major_formatter(cticker.LongitudeFormatter())

        axs[row,col].add_feature(cartopy.feature.BORDERS)
        axs[row,col].gridlines(alpha=0.6, linewidth=0.5)

Example how to select seasons in python (without cdo)¶

In [16]:
# group by season 
djf_timeIdx = data.groupby("time.season").groups["DJF"]
jja_timeIdx = data.groupby("time.season").groups["JJA"]

# get data by index
djf_data = [x for i, x in enumerate(data["tas"]) if i in djf_timeIdx]
jja_data = [x for i, x in enumerate(data["tas"]) if i in jja_timeIdx]
In [17]:
# create xr.Dataarray from regular array / list
ds_djf = xr.DataArray(
    data = djf_data,
    dims = ["time", "lat", "lon"],
    coords = dict(
        time = [data["time"][i].values.ravel()[0] for i,x in enumerate(data["tas"]) if i in djf_timeIdx],
        lat = data["lat"], lon = data["lon"])
).transpose("lat", "lon", "time")
#ds_djf.to_netcdf("djf_tas_dataset.nc") # save as .nc file

ds_jja = xr.DataArray(
    data = jja_data,
    dims = ["time", "lat", "lon"],
    coords = dict(
        time = [data["time"][i].values.ravel()[0] for i,x in enumerate(data["tas"]) if i in jja_timeIdx],
        lat = data["lat"], lon = data["lon"])
).transpose("lat", "lon", "time")
